            <h1 class="title">
                Motivation and Relevance
            </h1>
        </div>
        <br>
        <div class="container">
            I started this project as part of my final year project in Computer Engineering, as supervised by Prof.
            Stephen Barrett. My aims and goals for the project have stemmed from an interest in what makes a good
            team, and what exactly makes an individual progress. Is it through the influence of peers? Is it
            through exposure to new styles? Is it from jumping straight into the deep end?
        </div>
        <br>
        <div class="container">
            My approach to this started out simply - analyse a repository and generate information about a user per
            commit. Each commit has to follow a simple atomic axiom - only one user can commit at a time. This infers
            that contributions can be mapped to the progression of the project as a whole through Halstead complexity
            metrics, and show what governs the true contributions by users in a project. The general complexities
            and raw metrics associated per commit also allow the progression of a user to be shown over time in a
            sense of the change of their contributions, and the change of the complexities over time.
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

